As a developer,
I want to build a dedicated data connector using the google-cloud-storage Python client,
So that the MCP server has a modular, reusable, and secure way to interact with Google Cloud Storage to manage and retrieve files (blobs).

Acceptance Criteria

These conditions must be met for the feature to function as requested:

Folder Structure

All code for this connector must be developed and contained within the /connectors/cloud_storage directory at the root of the repository.

Client Initialization

The connector must initialize the Cloud Storage client seamlessly (relying on Google Application Default Credentials so it works locally via impersonation and in the cloud).

Connector Capabilities

The connector (a Python class) must implement methods to handle the following operations:

Create: Upload a new file (blob) to a specified bucket. It should support both string/bytes content and uploading from a local file path. (mime-type must be identified/specified)
Read: Download (in memory - bytes) and return the contents of a specific file (blob) from a bucket, so the agent can read it.
Update: Overwrite the contents of an existing file (blob) or update its metadata (like content-type).
List: Retrieve a list of files (blobs) within a specific bucket. It must support filtering by a prefix (to simulate folder structures).
Definition of Done

Code is fully typed (using Python type hints) and includes clear docstrings for every method.
When necessary, use data types directly from the google-cloud-storage library (for example: google.cloud.storage.blob.Blob or google.cloud.storage.bucket.Bucket).
Code passes standard formatting and linting checks (e.g., using ruff).
Unit tests are implemented for the connector methods (mocking the Storage client to avoid actual cloud network calls during CI).
A basic README.md or usage example is added inside /connectors/cloud_storage to show how to instantiate and call the connector.
The PR is successfully reviewed and merged into the main development branch.